# {{lb|en|transitive}}
## {{lb|en|also|figuratively}} To [[loosen]] or [[undo#Verb|undo]] (something that [[entangle]]s, [[fasten]]s, [[hold#Verb|holds]], or [[interlock]]s).
##: {{synonyms|en|disengage|loose|unfasten|untie}}
##* {{circa|1598}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Henry V (play)|Henry V}}'', Act I, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=henry5&Act=1&Scene=1&Scope=scene]</sup>
##*: The Gordian knot of it he will '''unloose''', / Familiar as his garter:
##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Lear|act=II|scene=ii|page=292|column=1|passage=[S]uch ſmiling rogues as theſe, / Like Rats oft bite the holy cords a twaine, / Which are [[too|t']] intrince, [[to|t']] '''vnlooſe''': {{...}}}}
##* '''1611''', ''{{w|King James Version}} of the {{w|Bible}}'', {{w|Gospel of Mark|Mark}} 1:7,<sup>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Mark+1&version=KJV]</sup>
##*: There cometh one mightier than I after me, the latchet of whose shoes I am not worthy to stoop down and '''unloose'''.
##* '''1762''', {{w|Laurence Sterne}}, ''{{w|The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy}}'', London: T. Becket & P.A. Dehondt, Volume 5, Chapter 3, p. 34,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/lifeandopinions01unkngoog]</sup>
##*: Death opens the gate of fame, and shuts the gate of envy after it,—it '''unlooses''' the chain of the captive, and puts the bondsman’s task into another man’s hands.
##* '''1900''', {{w|Bret Harte}}, “A Niece of Snapshot Harry’s” in ''From Sand Hill to Pine'', Boston: Houghton Mifflin, p. 64,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/topifromsandhill00hartrich]</sup>
##*: Forgetting his disgust, Brice tore away the shirt and '''unloosed''' the belt.
##* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=April|author=Cecil J. Allen|title=Locomotive Running Past and Present|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=209|text={{...}} there was plenty of opportunity to modernise in the years up to 1939, but since then the Second World War and its aftermath of expenditure rigidly controlled by Government held up any progress until at last the purse-strings were '''unloosed''' five years ago. But an enormous amount of leeway needs to be made up.}}
## {{lb|en|also figuratively}} To [[relax]] or [[slacken]] (something that [[clasp#Verb|clasps]] or [[grip#Verb|grips]], such as the [[arm#Noun|arms]] or [[hand#Noun|hands]]).
##: {{synonyms|en|let go|unclasp}}
## To [[free#Verb|free]] (someone or something) from a [[constraint]]; {{lb|en|figuratively}} to [[release#Verb|release]] (something which has been [[suppress]]ed, such as [[emotion]]s or [[objectionable]] [[thing]]s).
##: {{synonyms|en|liberate|set free|unleash|vent}}
##* {{circa|1590}} {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Henry VI, Part 2}}'', Act V, Scene 1,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=henry6p2&Act=5&Scene=1&Scope=scene]</sup>
##*: Then, York, '''unloose''' thy long-imprison’d thoughts
##*: And let thy tongue be equal with thy heart.
##* '''1717''', {{w|Laurence Eusden}} (translator), “The Story of Pyramus and Thisbe” in {{w|John Dryden}} (editor), ''{{w|Ovid}}’s {{w|Metamorphoses}} in Fifteen Books. Translated by the most Eminent Hands'', London: Jacob Tonson, p. 109,<sup>[http://name.umdl.umich.edu/004871123.0001.000]</sup>
##*: Thus did the melancholy Tale conclude, / And a short, silent Interval ensu’d. / The next in Birth '''unloos’d''' her artful Tongue, / And drew attentive all the Sister-Throng.
##* '''1827''', {{w|Nathaniel Parker Willis}}, “Extract from a Poem delivered at the departure of the senior class of Yale College, in 1826” in ''Sketches'', Boston: S. G. Goodrich, p. 92,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/sketchesnp00willrich]</sup>
##*: Press on! for it is godlike to '''unloose''' / The spirit, and forget yourself in thought; {{...}}
##* {{RQ:Baldwin Mountain|part=3|page=216|year_published=1970|passage=He would weep again, his heart insisted, for now his weeping had begun; he would rage again, said the shifting air, for the lions of rage had been '''unloosed'''; he would be in darkness again, in fire again, now that he had seen the fire and the darkness.}}
